<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="548" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,732,1803]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1020,1047]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Forewing length is 
<quantity box="[546,667,1021,1047]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" unit="mm" value="13.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="12.0">12–14 mm</quantity>
in males and 
<quantity box="[823,966,1020,1047]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.475" metricValueMax="1.55" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" unit="mm" value="14.75" valueMax="15.5" valueMin="14.0">14–15.5 mm</quantity>
in females. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[1103,1290,1021,1047]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[1103,1290,1021,1047]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Barsine gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from other relatives by its not wavy antemedial line and not enlarged connection of antemedial and medial transverse lines of forewing (that is also not enlarged in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2019" box="[807,998,1093,1119]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kanchenjunga">
<emphasis box="[807,998,1093,1119]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. kanchenjunga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only). The male genital capsule of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2019" box="[481,596,1129,1155]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dejeani">
<emphasis box="[481,596,1129,1155]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. dejeani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its shorter and more curved uncus, longer tegumen being straight, the presence of a dentate plate of manica, narrower valva, less developed medial costal process, smaller distal costal process directed distally, smaller distal membranous lobe of valva, the absence of a basal lobe of sacculus, and trigonal, narrower and more prominent distal saccular process. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[1026,1151,1237,1263]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[1026,1151,1237,1263]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is longer and less curved than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2019" box="[286,400,1273,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dejeani">
<emphasis box="[286,400,1273,1299]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. dejeani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The vesica of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[573,697,1273,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[573,697,1273,1299]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Černý" authorityYear="2019" box="[926,1039,1273,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dejeani">
<emphasis box="[926,1039,1273,1299]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. dejeani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its unilobate and weakly granulated subbasal diverticulum, dorsal medial diverticulum bearing granulation and a narrow cluster of small but robust cornuti, smaller ventral medial diverticulum with smaller cornuti, smaller distal diverticulum being membranous, and smaller basal plate of vesica ejaculatorius. In the female genitalia, the antrum is broad, with a deep and narrow medial concavity (whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[482,587,1417,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inflexa">
<emphasis box="[482,587,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. inflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[639,762,1417,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[639,762,1417,1443]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is narrow and caliciform), the ductus bursae is long (that is much shorter in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[360,467,1453,1479]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inflexa">
<emphasis box="[360,467,1453,1479]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. inflexa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[521,645,1453,1479]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[521,645,1453,1479]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the corpus bursae is large and bears spinulose scobination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="548" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,732,1803]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,344,1489,1515]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Remarks. 1.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Holloway, J. D." box="[351,544,1489,1515]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" pagination="279 - 486" refId="ref9138" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2001) The moths of Borneo: family Arctiidae, subfamily Lithosiinae. Malayan Nature Journal, 7, 279 - 486." type="journal article" year="2001">Holloway (2001)</bibRefCitation>
has restored 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moore" authorityYear="1878" box="[694,787,1489,1515]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gloriosa">
<emphasis box="[694,787,1489,1515]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">gloriosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to a valid species. However, the male specimen from NE 
<collectingCountry box="[151,209,1525,1551]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">India</collectingCountry>
dissected by Holloway (slide BMNH(E) Arct.-5273) is not conspecific to the 
<typeStatus box="[1080,1178,1525,1551]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">holotype</typeStatus>
and belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin, 2018" authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Barsine" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="garo">
<emphasis box="[1354,1436,1526,1551]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">B. garo</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Volynkin, A. V." box="[151,329,1561,1587]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref9423" refString="Volynkin, A. V. (2018) Four new species of the genus Barsine Walker, 1854 (Lepidoptera: Erebidae, Arctiinae) from Oriental Region. Far Eastern Entomologist, 358, 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.25221 / fee. 358.1" type="journal article" year="2018">Volynkin, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[340,362,1561,1587]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">2.</emphasis>
There is a slight variation in the female genitalia structure: compared to those of the 
<typeStatus box="[1338,1436,1561,1587]" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">holotype</typeStatus>
female from Khasi Hills (
<figureCitation box="[443,527,1597,1623]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–53" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1887,1912]" captionTargetBox="[177,1435,166,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,166,1867]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 48–53. Barsine spp.: female genitalia. 48, B. gloriosa, holotype, NE India, slide AV2886 Volynkin; 49, B. gloriosa, N Myanmar, slide ZSM Arct. 53/2017 Volynkin; 50, B. hreblayi, paratype, N Thailand, slide MWM 33684 Volynkin; 51, B. flavodiscalis, Borneo, slide AV2831 Volynkin; 52, B. cruciata, W Malaysia, slide MWM 33602 Volynkin; 53, B. siberuta, paratype, Indonesia, Siberut Isl., slide MWM 34600 Volynkin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3450022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3450022/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
), in the 
<collectingCountry box="[621,730,1597,1623]" name="Myanmar" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
population the antrum has a slightly deeper medial concavity, and the posterior section of ductus bursae is slightly broader (
<figureCitation box="[837,921,1633,1659]" captionStart="FIGURES 48–53" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1887,1912]" captionTargetBox="[177,1435,166,1845]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1435,166,1867]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 48–53. Barsine spp.: female genitalia. 48, B. gloriosa, holotype, NE India, slide AV2886 Volynkin; 49, B. gloriosa, N Myanmar, slide ZSM Arct. 53/2017 Volynkin; 50, B. hreblayi, paratype, N Thailand, slide MWM 33684 Volynkin; 51, B. flavodiscalis, Borneo, slide AV2831 Volynkin; 52, B. cruciata, W Malaysia, slide MWM 33602 Volynkin; 53, B. siberuta, paratype, Indonesia, Siberut Isl., slide MWM 34600 Volynkin." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3450022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3450022/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="548">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
). However, male genitalia of both populations show no differences.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
